      "details": "Create a tests/integration/ directory containing an automated harness that covers all major subsystems:\n\n1. **ACP / Session layer** — session init, tool-loop execution, session persistence (save/load), DNA injection, knowledge pack loading.\n2. **Router / Backend** — GrokBackend request/response round-trip with mock HTTP server; RouterResponse field mapping; tool-call dispatch; max-iteration guard.\n3. **Tool registry** — every registered tool (read_file, write_file, replace, list_directory, glob_search, search_file_content, run_shell_command, web_search, web_fetch, save_memory, task_get, task_create, task_update, execute_task_graph, spawn_agent, fork_agent, mcp_call, lsp_query, notebook_edit, execute_skill, cron_create, etc.) is exercised with valid args, invalid args, and edge-case inputs.\n4. **Security / path policy** — trusted directory enforcement, external-access flag, path traversal rejection.\n5. **Task tools** — task_create → task_get → task_update lifecycle; Format A/B/C normalisation; .bak recovery; atomic save (.tmp rename).\n6. **Memory subsystem** — long-term memory save/recall, episodic memory, tool history, skill memory/affinity.\n7. **Bayesian router** — priors load, route decision, profile persistence.\n8. **Config loading** — config.toml parsing, env-var overrides, missing-file defaults.\n9. **CLI commands** — chat, settings, tools, health commands via process spawn or direct fn call.\n10. **Error paths** — network timeout/retry (mock), corrupt JSON recovery, missing required fields, unknown tool rejection.\n\nUse wiremock or httpmock for HTTP mocking. Use tempfile for isolated file-system state. Every test must be deterministic and run offline. Add a CI-ready Makefile target and document the harness in Doc/testing.md.",
